<HEADLINE>
<P>
2 BIOSPHERE VETERANS ARE ARRESTED AFTER PROJECT SABOTAGED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Two people who lived inside Biosphere 2 for two years were arrested Wednesday 
for allegedly breaking into the sealed environmental experiment and leaving the 
doors open so outside air could get in. 
</P>
<P>
 Abigail Alling, who has been taking responsibility for Monday's intrusion in 
calls to reporters across the country, was arrested at a Tucson motel with 
fellow crew member Mark Van Thillo.They each face felony charges of burglary 
and criminal property damage. 
</P>
<P>
 Alling and Van Thillo, among eight people who lived in the sealed dome for two 
years ending Sept. 26, are employees of the project's operator, Space 
Biospheres Ventures. 
</P>
<P>
 Both were suspended from their jobs with the project last week by a 
court-appointed receiver representing the controversial project's financial 
backer, Texas billionaire Edward P. Bass. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA040794-0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 029869 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
April 7, 1994, Thursday, Southland Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
