<HEADLINE>
<P>
MEDIA: TWO VIEWS OF NEW SECTION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 I am writing to you to respond to the new "magazine" section in my Thursday 
L.A. Times. Although you call it "new" and "exciting," etc., it is another 
example where we are given less, while having it called more. 
</P>
<P>
 I really enjoyed reading the San Gabriel Valley section on Thursday and 
Sunday. You have had interesting feature stories on the area, some of which I 
frequently sent to my brother-in-law who recently moved to Denver and who grew 
up in Glendora. I enjoyed the coverage because I live in Pomona and work in 
Pasadena. 
</P>
<P>
 "Greatly disappointed" is the way I would describe myself upon seeing the new 
Thursday magazine. Since we no longer receive local coverage on Sundays, it has 
to make up for two good-size sections. The magazine format seems much more 
abbreviated and edited. Most of the stories do not extend beyond the first page 
of the story at all -- the articles seem much shorter! 
</P>
<P>
 I really wish you would reconsider this move. Yes, we sometimes get a San 
Gabriel story in the Metro section, etc., but the old two days per week section 
was greatly superior in length and breadth of the articles. 
</P>
<P>
 LARRY KRIEGER 
</P>
<P>
 Pomona  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Your new format of magazine/tabloid came again this morning. I am impressed by 
the way these sections make reading more attractive. 
</P>
<P>
 Seems to me both the news articles and the ads are more "smaller town" types 
that speak to me, who's been a big-city resident for 45 years. 
</P>
<P>
 Thank you for the freshness. 
</P>
<P>
 JAMES PARROTT 
</P>
<P>
 Pasadena  
</P>
