<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Kenneth R. Weiss 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 WHO CARES? It's an ugly thought, but Thousand Oaks' annual awards for the most 
beautiful gas station, apartment complex and industrial center may soon fade 
away because of public apathy. . . . Councilman Frank Schillo thought the 
city-beautiful awards would encourage general sprucing up of homes or 
storefronts. But no one has applied in any of the categories this year. "Is 
anybody interested in this?" asks Schillo, who is running for county 
supervisor. "If not, I'm not going to spend my time on this. I've got a lot of 
other things I could be doing." 
</P>
<P>
 RAPID FIRE: The same folks criticized for threatening sea lions and dolphins 
with underwater test explosions now want to test-fire a huge Gatling gun next 
to elephant seal breeding grounds on San Nicolas Island (B1). . . . The Navy 
proposes setting up the big gun on the island 60 miles off the coast. Usually 
mounted on ships, the gun unleashes a torrent of armor-piercing bullets that 
can knock down an incoming missile. The state Coastal Commission was horrified 
at first, but now believes the test poses no serious risk to endangered 
species. 
</P>
<P>
 FLOWER STORM: Last year's wildfires have wiped the hillsides clean for an 
explosion of springtime wildflowers (Ventura County Life, Page 24). The burn 
areas in the Santa Monica Mountains boast dozens of varieties normally choked 
by the thick layer of chaparral. . . . Park rangers also report sightings of 
the rare chocolate lily. "We don't see it very often," Ranger Mark Boehler 
says. "But it's coming up in quite a few places." 
</P>
<P>
 PASS THE HAT: The helmets looked innocent enough, patina-on-bronze replicas of 
headgear worn by Greek Olympians 3,000 years ago. But when Oxnard City Council 
members opened the helmet boxes and found out each could be worth $3,000, they 
started a scramble to unload the gifts from a Korean businessman (B1). . . . 
"We simply can't accept gifts of that value, so we decided to donate it to the 
library," Councilman Michael Plisky said. Actually, public officials can accept 
gifts, but must declare items worth at least $50. 
</P>
