<HEADLINE>
<P>
SANTA CLARITA / ANTELOPE VALLEY; SWASTIKA PAINTING MARKS 2ND HATE INCIDENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DOUGLAS ALGER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A 10-foot-tall swastika painted in ketchup on a Canyon Country driveway Easter 
Sunday was the second hate incident in the city in less than two weeks, 
authorities said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
 Racist flyers were discovered in student lockers at Placerita Junior High 
School in Newhall 13 days earlier. But Los Angeles County sheriff's 
investigators believe that the swastika and flyers came from different sources. 
</P>
<P>
 "It would really be a surprise if they're related," said Sgt. Howard Fairchild 
of the Santa Clarita Valley Sheriff's Station. "It (the swastika) is not the 
m.o. of the other knuckleheads." 
</P>
<P>
 Two men -- one Latino and one African American -- live in the home on Basel 
Street where the swastika was painted. Authorities believe that the drawing was 
probably a nasty prank aimed at the two men specifically, rather than the 
handiwork of neo-Nazis trying to spread the racist sentiment. 
</P>
<P>
 Similar Nazi-type graffiti appears about two or three times a year in Santa 
Clarita, Fairchild said. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think the thing with the flyers are people from out of the area trying to 
spread a message here," Fairchild said. "I hope this (the ketchup swastika) is 
just one incident that's not going to be repeated." 
</P>
<P>
 More than 1,000 leaflets bearing derogatory remarks about Latinos and Jews 
were found at Placerita Junior High March 21, making the incident the largest 
distribution of hate literature in northern Los Angeles County in memory. 
School officials used the incident to begin discussions about cultural 
diversity, racism and tolerance. 
</P>
<P>
 A smaller batch of anti-Latino flyers -- about a dozen -- was discovered in 
soda packs, backpacks and women's hygiene products at several Santa Clarita 
grocery stores in December. 
</P>
<P>
 In both incidents involving the printed materials, the leaflets gave a phone 
number for the White Aryan Resistance group in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 Authorities say hate flyers are protected by the First Amendment, and those 
responsible for distributing them on school campuses or in a store could only 
be charged with trespassing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
