<HEADLINE>
<P>
CASH-CRAZED CROWD TRASHES LIBRARY SHELVES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Ft. Worth Central Library was in shambles Wednesday after more than 500 
people responded to a radio station's publicity stunt by rushing through the 
aisles, climbing shelves and throwing books to the floor in search of money. 
</P>
<P>
 A disc jockey had announced Tuesday evening that Dallas-based country radio 
station KYNG-FM used $5 and $10 bills as bookmarks in the fiction section. 
</P>
<P>
 The library staff and a host of volunteers were busy Wednesday sorting through 
more than 3,000 books that frenzied listeners tossed on the floor. 
</P>
<P>
 "People started climbing the bookshelves; they started climbing on each other, 
and books became airborne," library spokeswoman Marsha Anderson said. Some of 
the books ended up with ripped pages and broken spines. 
</P>
<P>
 It is unclear how much money was actually put in the books. The station claims 
it was only about $100, but the library staff did not know anything about it. 
</P>
<P>
 They were caught by surprise when hundreds of people began pouring through the 
doors, saying they had heard $10,000 was hidden in the books. 
</P>
<P>
 A KYNG spokesman said the disc jockey only wanted to boost public interest in 
the library by giving away about $100, and had no idea why listeners assumed 
that as much as $10,000 was at stake. 
</P>
<P>
 After several unsuccessful attempts to reach the radio station, library 
workers tried to restore calm by falsely announcing that the money had been 
found and the contest was over. 
</P>
</TEXT>
