<HEADLINE>
<P>
INSIDE LINE: OC HIGH: STUDENT NEWS & VIEWS; SAT VERDICT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Joslin Gemsch; junior, Capistrano Valley 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The first wave of students has now undergone the newly revised Scholastic 
Aptitude Test, now named the Scholastic Assessment Test I (SAT I) and 
administered for the first time March 19. 
</P>
<P>
 Capistrano Valley High School senior Marcus McGee thought it "definitely was 
easier." 
</P>
<P>
 But, McGee added, "As usual, the test contained words I had never heard before 
in my life." 
</P>
<P>
 Emilie Scott, a junior at Capistrano Valley High, said, "The beginning parts 
of the math and English were too easy, and I was getting a bad feeling. The 
last part of the math was really hard, though." 
</P>
<P>
 Harder or not, the true test of SAT I's difficulty will be decided after the 
scores are received. Joslin Gemsch; junior, Capistrano Valley 
</P>
</TEXT>
